text: When you read double standard articles about Tesla, please ask why. Maybe there’s a good reason that isn’t obvious.

author: elonmusk
text: Reality is a Tesla, like most electric cars, is over 500% *less* likely to catch fire than combustion engine cars, which carry massive amounts of highly flammable fuel. Why is this never mentioned?

author: elonmusk
text: Over a million combustion engine (it’s right there in the name!) car fires per year & thousands of deaths, but one Tesla car fire with no injuries gets biggest headlines. Why the double standard? This is a real question.

author: elonmusk
text: Those who predicted Tesla & EVs would be dead & autonomy would never happen are same people attacking Tesla today for 6-12 month delays, while ignoring major automakers 5+ years late. Why the double standard?

author: tsrandall
text: Finally, Tesla’s product roadmap is probably the best in the biz—if they can stick to it. Our analysis last year showed that Musk typically blows his own deadlines by about 50% of the original projection 9/ https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2019-01-07/tesla-s-life-after-hell-7-charts-show-musk-on-firmer-footing …pic.twitter.com/789nxIQO1o

author: tsrandall
text: Once Tesla started cranking out Model 3s, its cash flows made a U-turn. Every analyst surveyed by Bloomberg now expects a Q4 profit—a reversal from last spring. 2019 free cash flow expectations flipped from -$795 million to +$837 million 5/ https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2019-01-07/tesla-s-life-after-hell-7-charts-show-musk-on-firmer-footing …pic.twitter.com/xXtMxZOIeX

author: tsrandall
text: In the closing weeks of 2018, Tesla’s market cap overtook Daimler’s as the third most-valuable automaker—they’ve since gone back and forth—even though Tesla is nowhere close to the revenue, earnings or capital resources of these global competitors 4/ https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2019-01-07/tesla-s-life-after-hell-7-charts-show-musk-on-firmer-footing …pic.twitter.com/UDXJ5PhTUt

author: tsrandall
text: In the second half of 2018, the Model 3 was the fifth best-selling sedan in the U.S.—outsold only by Toyotas and Hondas—despite an average selling price of more than $55k. No other car brought in more revenue in the U.S. 3/ https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2019-01-07/tesla-s-life-after-hell-7-charts-show-musk-on-firmer-footing …pic.twitter.com/hio0a1vhYB

author: tsrandall
text: First up: Tesla’s production numbers. After struggling to make the Model 3 for 18 months, everything changed in Q3. It took 10 years for Tesla to sell its first half-million electric cars. It’ll take just 15 months to reach its first million 2/ https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2019-01-07/tesla-s-life-after-hell-7-charts-show-musk-on-firmer-footing …pic.twitter.com/tJS870MGdR
